tten authors. The second part discusses Turkey as the “other” of the West and the way authors writing in Turkish challenged orientalist representations. Thus this book prepares the ground for a history of literature which uncouples language and religion and recreates the spaces of dialogue and exchange that have existed in late Ottoman Turkey between members of various ethno-religious communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLiterature and societyzTurkey. 0aOrientalism. 0aReligion and literaturezTurkey. 0aTurkish literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aTurkish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aTurkish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aArmeno-Turkish.  aJewish.  aJudaeo-Turkish.  aKaramanli.  aMiddle East.  aOther.  aOttoman literature.  acomparative.  acriticism.  aculture.  aessays.  afiction.  anon-Muslim authors.  aorientalism.  aphilosophy.  apoetry.  areligious minorities.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074321008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978164469580740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644695807423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/is